SIMPLE: circinate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Circinate
<hw>Cir"ci*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>circinatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>circinare</ets> to make round, fr.
<ets>circinus</ets> a pair of compasses, from Gr. <?/ a circle.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Rolled together downward, the tip occupying the
center; -- a term used in reference to foliation or leafing, as in
ferns.</def> <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Circinate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Circinate
<hw>Cir"ci*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make a
circle around; to encompass.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bailey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Circination</ent>⟦br⟧
